    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Payments Overview",
            Slug = "payments-overview",
            Summary = "What the Payments module does, standalone vs integrated mode, payment methods, and how payments apply to invoices.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/payments"]""",
            Tags = """["payments","accounting"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payments Overview\n\nThe Payments module records incoming customer payments and applies them to outstanding invoices. It is part of the accounting boundary — meaning it operates in **standalone mode** when no external accounting provider (QuickBooks, Xero, etc.) is connected. When an accounting provider is integrated, payments sync from the external system and the module becomes read-only.\n\n### Standalone vs Integrated Mode\n\n**Standalone mode (no accounting provider):** You have full control. Create payments, apply them to invoices, delete unapplied payments, and track payment history directly in QB Engineer. This is the default for shops that don't use an external accounting system.\n\n**Integrated mode (accounting provider connected):** A blue banner appears at the top of the Payments page indicating that payments are managed by the connected provider (e.g., QuickBooks Online). Payment data syncs automatically — you can view payments but cannot create, edit, or delete them from QB Engineer. All payment operations happen in the accounting system.\n\n### Payment Methods\n\nEvery payment records how it was received. The supported methods are:\n- **Cash** — physical currency received\n- **Check** — paper check (use the Reference Number field to record the check number)\n- **Credit Card** — card payment (reference number can hold the last four digits or transaction ID)\n- **Bank Transfer** — ACH or direct bank transfer\n- **Wire** — wire transfer (reference number holds the wire confirmation)\n- **Other** — any method not covered above\n\n### Applying Payments to Invoices\n\nA payment can be applied to one or more invoices. Each application specifies which invoice receives how much of the payment. This enables:\n\n- **Full payment** — the entire payment amount covers one invoice exactly\n- **Partial payment** — only part of the payment goes to an invoice (the invoice moves to Partially Paid status)\n- **Split payment** — one payment covers portions of multiple invoices\n- **Unapplied payment** — a payment (or portion of it) is recorded without being tied to any invoice yet. The unapplied amount shows in the table and is highlighted in the detail view.\n\nWhen a payment application fully covers an invoice's remaining balance, that invoice automatically moves to Paid status. If a partial amount is applied, the invoice moves to Partially Paid.\n\n### Validation Rules\n\nThe total of all applications on a payment cannot exceed the payment amount. Each individual application amount must be positive, and it cannot exceed the remaining balance on its target invoice.\n\n### When to Use Payments\n\n- When you receive a check, cash, or electronic payment from a customer\n- When you need to record a partial payment against a large invoice\n- When a single customer payment covers multiple invoices\n- When you need to track unapplied payments (money received before invoicing)\n- When reviewing a customer's payment history by opening a payment","sections":[]}"""
        });

